<div id="review_3189680042" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3189680042" />
    <a title="William" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/100961745-william"><img alt="William" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1601796146p2/100961745.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3189680042?book_show_action=true">Jul 15, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="William" class="user" itemprop="url" name="William" href="/user/show/100961745-william">William</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780679722410" href="/book/show/464261.Spring_Snow">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/100961745-william?shelf=bookshelf">bookshelf</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/100961745-william?shelf=1900s-ce">1900s-ce</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/100961745-william?shelf=japanese">japanese</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/100961745-william?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/100961745-william?shelf=mishima">mishima</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/100961745-william?shelf=sea-of-fertility">sea-of-fertility</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3189680042" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15557060848643878691">A novel I can scarcely find positive or negative words for, not until I finish the rest of the books in the Sea of Fertility trilogy do I see myself being able to articulate a position on how well they stand up to criticism, but my thoughts as of just finishing Spring Snow, here&apos;s what I have to say. To me, Mishima&apos;s characters are passionate, shadowy beings, their thoughts are revealing speculations on their own deepest feelings, and they haunted by this constancy of self-consciousness amidst t</span>
  <span id="freeText15557060848643878691" style="display:none">A novel I can scarcely find positive or negative words for, not until I finish the rest of the books in the Sea of Fertility trilogy do I see myself being able to articulate a position on how well they stand up to criticism, but my thoughts as of just finishing Spring Snow, here's what I have to say. To me, Mishima's characters are passionate, shadowy beings, their thoughts are revealing speculations on their own deepest feelings, and they haunted by this constancy of self-consciousness amidst their changing lives. I was truly moved by the way Mishima almost paints with prose the rawness of human duality, how the emotional tones are bursting and swelling like pools of iridescent lifeblood. And many of these characters can always be seen as both genuinely wretched and momentaneously beautiful, in the case of the protagonist Kiyoaki who excelled at provoking empathy from me, even though I never felt asked to excuse his lack of moral goodness. Much of the novel pretty intensely punishes him, painfully, but washed in the watery streaks of Mishima's eminent contrast of light and dark, we cannot help but pity him, we want whoever is transforming these events into such vivid images to somehow change the fabric of what actually happened. Another day I'll have a greater perspective informed by the rest of the tetralogy, but so far, I do find myself restless to enter into the next incarnation.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15557060848643878691" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


